user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following metal_dma_unmap code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 8.13.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 is A pointer should point to a const-qualified type whenever possible.

</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of metal_dma_unmap.
```c
void metal_dma_unmap(struct metal_device *dev,
		  uint32_t dir,
		  struct metal_sg *sg,
		  int nents)
{
	/* memory barrier */
	if (dir == METAL_DMA_DEV_R)
		/* If it is device read, apply memory write fence. */
		atomic_thread_fence(memory_order_release);
	else
		/*If it is device write or r/w, apply memory r/w fence */
		atomic_thread_fence(memory_order_acq_rel);

	if (!dev || !dev->bus->ops.dev_dma_unmap || !sg)
		return;
	dev->bus->ops.dev_dma_unmap(dev->bus,
			dev, dir, sg, nents);
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The function pointer dev_dma_unmap declares its sg parameter as struct metal_sg *sg (non-const), while the wrapper metal_dma_unmap does not modify the sg contents and merely forwards the pointer to the bus operation. If implementations of dev_dma_unmap are not expected to modify the scatter-gather entries, the parameter should be declared const (const struct metal_sg *sg). Because the pointer is not const-qualified where it could be, this violates MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13.
</scenario>
<additional code>Here are the definitions of symbols that are close to the target function metal_dma_unmap:
struct metal_bus_ops {
	void		(*bus_close)(struct metal_bus *bus);
